entry.title: Reland "[sync]Fix ShouldGetTypesWithUnsyncedDataFromSyncService integration test"
entry.content:
This is a reland of commit 86e6619e36f23185c381d418c1e4016ddd3c1304



Verified locally.



The previous version had a race condition due to commit response not

being processed. This CL fixes that by using a

CommittedAllNudgedChangesChecker instead.



Original change's description:

> [sync]Fix ShouldGetTypesWithUnsyncedDataFromSyncService integration test

>

> Previously the test was flaky. This is because it relied on if there

> exists some unsynced data for PREFERENCES. This is not super reliable

> since many different components regularly interact with PREFERENCES and

> there maybe something happening behind the scene which would give false

> results when we expect there to be no unsynced data for PREFERENCES.

>

> This CL fixes that and also reduces the complexity of the test by only

> using a single datatype - BOOKMARKS for the test.

>

entry.title: Add workaround for last_active_time underlying type transition
entry.content:
Before https://crrev.com/c/4905251, last_active_time was stored

as a base::TimeTicks internal value. After the CL, it is stored

as microseconds since Windows epoch.

TimeTicks' internal representation (i.e. the old persisted value)

does *not* match "microseconds since Windows epoch", which

is leading to an issue where the values serialized with a

TimeTicks origin were deserialized very far in the past when

looked from a base::Time epoch.



This CL adds a code path that tries to detect if the value was stored

in the old format, and if yes transform it to the new format. Once

converted to the new format, the value will be re-serialized in the

new format.



It is a temporary workaround that should be removed once most users

have converted their last_active_time to the new format.



This is using banned functions as this is what was used previously

(see https://crrev.com/c/4905251).

entry.title: Fix strings are translated, but do not reflect in the build
entry.content:
Fixes things so `ph` tags work correctly.

* Assuming the original string in the grd file is

`Download error: $1error-int.`

* TC generates the IDs based on the fingerprint for

`Download error: DOWNLOAD_ERROR.`.

* `create_string_rc.py` was generating the IDs based on the fingerprint

for `Download error: $1.`, but now generates it the same way TC does it.

* `create_string_rc.py` was also not setting placeholders for the `ph`

tags in the XTB handling, that has been fixed as well.



There are only 3 users of `generate_embedded_i18n`:

https://source.chromium.org/search?q=generate_embedded_i18n.



Of these, `updater` (and probably the chrome installer in small measure,

since I got a failure in

`ShellUtilShortcutTest.CreateMultipleStartMenuShortcutsAndRemoveFolder`

with an earlier patchset http://shortn/_7FyICInFcO) are the ones using

replaceable `ph` parameters.



For the most part, the Chrome Installer and the GAIA credentials

provider are only using hardcoded strings, based on the IDs in

`chrome/installer/util/prebuild/create_installer_string_rc.py`, and GAIA

uses a separate `.grd` file.



Fixed: 1505642

entry.title: [CVV Storage] Fix unintended CVC number deletion for Butter users
entry.content:
If a user has enabled butter, CVC numbers can be unintentionally

deleted today:



CVCs are not stored in Wallet on the server but in a separate data

source. When a full sync from Wallet happens, the card data from the

server does not contain CVCs. When Chrome replaces locally cached

credit card data with the new data from Wallet, the CVCs get deleted

locally as well as from the Sync servers.



This CL preserves the CVC numbers similarly to how we already preserve

metadata: Before replacing a credit card, we check whether data for

the same credit card already existed and preserve a stored CVC number

if it existed.

entry.title: Make the data pipe size in RaceNetworkRequest configurable
entry.content:
In ServiceWorkerRaceNetworkRequestURLLoaderClient, two mojo pipes are

newly created in the constructor. If the ServiceWorkerAutoPreload

feature is enabled, this happens basically per resource requests,

inclusding subresources.



We're seeing SIGBUS error increase on Linux dev channel, in which we run

the ServiceWorkerAutoPreload experiment now. This may happen on the

enviroment having small /dev/shm space.



This CL makes the buffer size of the data pipe configurable so that we

can check if the resource usage of mojo data pipe causes the error or

not, by passing the smaller number as a buffer size for the data pipe

creation via the feature param.

entry.title: [GridNG] Reject parsing `auto-fit` for subgrids
entry.content:
It turns out that subgrid only supports `auto-fill`, and not `auto-fit`.



= repeat( [ | auto-fill ], +)

"The variant is for adding line names to subgrids."



https://www.w3.org/TR/css-grid-2/#repeat-syntax



This was missed due to shared parsing code for subgrid and grid

auto-repeats, along with the fact that there were no tests for this

until recently.



This change simply rejects parsing of `auto-fit` when `subgrid` is

specified and removes the -expected.txt. With this change,

https://wpt.live/css/css-grid/subgrid/grid-template-invalid.html

passes.
